  "prompt": "What kind of first jobs do neuroscience majors tend to get?",
  "response": "Neuroscience majors typically have a variety of career paths available to them upon graduation. The specific roles can depend on their level of education, skills, and interests, but common entry-level jobs for neuroscience majors include:\n\n1. **Research Assistant/Technician**: Working in laboratory settings to assist with experiments, collect data, and perform analyses. This role is common in universities, research institutions, or biomedical companies.\n\n2. **Clinical Research Coordinator**: Managing the operational aspects of clinical trials, including participant recruitment, data collection, and regulatory compliance.\n\n3. **Pharmaceutical Sales Representative**: Utilizing their scientific background to effectively communicate the benefits and mechanisms of pharmaceutical products to healthcare providers.\n\n4. **Medical and Science Communications**: Working in medical writing, scientific journalism, or public relations for healthcare organizations, helping to translate complex scientific information into accessible formats.\n\n5. **Clinical Neuroscience Technician**: Positions like neurodiagnostic technologists, who conduct tests such as EEGs or MRI scans under the supervision of medical professionals.\n\n6. **Behavioral Health Technician**: Assisting in the delivery of mental health services, treatment plans, and monitoring patient progress in clinical settings.\n\n7. **Healthcare Consulting Analyst**: Working with firms that advise healthcare organizations, leveraging their understanding of neuroscience to analyze treatment efficacy, streamline operations, and support decision-making processes.\n\n8. **Biotech Technician**: Supporting the development and testing of new medical technologies and therapies in the biotechnology sector.\n\nThese roles provide valuable experience and can serve as stepping stones for further specialization or advancement within both clinical and research-focused careers.",
